I forgot to give it to you in class but our 'Seanfhocal' for this week is: =
'Ar mhuin na muice'
An Irish idiom literally meaning "on the pig's back<https://www.google.com/=
search?q=3Don+the+pig%27s+back&sca_esv=3Dbfda1312cc855ae4&sxsrf=3DANbL-n73V=
fOFYqJwsRl3GqhIjA7bjTnQFA%3A1768845456744&ei=3DkHBuaYWbLdidhbIP6f3B8Ao&oq=
=3Dar+mhuin+na+muice+&gs_lp=3DEgxnd3Mtd2l6LXNlcnAiEmFyIG1odWluIG5hIG11aWNlI=
CoCCAAyCxAAGIAEGJECGIoFMgYQABgWGB4yBhAAGBYYHjIGEAAYFhgeMgYQABgWGB4yBhAAGBYY=
HjIGEAAYFhgeMgYQABgWGB4yBhAAGBYYHjIGEAAYFhgeSOcMUNIDWNIDcAF4AJABAJgBfaAByAG=
qAQMxLjG4AQHIAQD4AQGYAgKgApcBwgIKEAAYsAMY1gQYR8ICDRAAGIAEGLADGEMYigWYAwCIBg=
GQBgaSBwMxLjGgB5gKsgcDMC4xuAeLAcIHBTItMS4xyAcRgAgA&sclient=3Dgws-wiz-serp&m=
stk=3DAUtExfCL7aKI1Z399wBkCuG2M9TxE2_jO6ID99x35VNYbJO6vx1MN4_QKXl3ZQs2CqgJK=
oJczjmHSoUpyTorWWLRYeOhmBFPUwkWVpO3ttNG77m0aRfnI1QJOa7iPVhf5pJAGWfVeZyslt4r=
PEz1S0lf3_PXGiBE3pKPt4THsP0Ge9hvJBu0dfy1IzZcupRqVEkkXhgy&csui=3D3&ved=3D2ah=
UKEwju55r1lpiSAxV-REEAHendI1IQgK4QegYIAQgAEAY>," used to say someone is doi=
ng great, in luck, well off, or "on top of the world," expressing a very po=
sitive situation or feeling prosperous. It's a traditional phrase from the =
17th century, often translated into English as being "in luck" or doing exc=
eptionally well, like getting a dream job or having good fortune.
ar =3D on, mhuin =3D back, na muice =3D of the pig

